{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511907"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:47:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:47:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11814"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11814"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.02,0.03,0.5,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4419"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102957"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4419"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11814"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85423"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"414"},{"type":"tags","id":"2171"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5364"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6306"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6352"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12212"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36277"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102957","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102957"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic after receiving a positive faecal occult blood test (FOBT) result. He has a medical history of ischaemic heart disease. His medications include perindopril, metoprolol, atorvastatin and aspirin. He has a sedentary lifestyle, is a non-smoker and drinks approximately four standard drinks of alcohol a week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 148/84 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His BMI is 32 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. The doctor explains the need for further investigations to rule out colon cancer and discusses potential risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following factors confers the most significant risk for the development of colorectal cancer in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["His sedentary lifestyle","His use of aspirin","His ischaemic heart disease","His BMI","His age"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EColorectal cancer (CRC) is being seen with increasing frequency, particularly in the younger age groups. Whilst the risk of CRC increases with age, about 10% of newly diagnosed cases occur in adults younger than the age of 50. This is termed early-onset colorectal cancer (EoCRC) and applies to the patient described in the stem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, the patient\u0027s \u003Cstrong\u003EBMI\u003C/strong\u003E of 32 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E, which falls in the obese category, confers the highest risk for colorectal cancer among the given options. A high BMI increases the risk of CRC and increases mortality. The risk of developing many types of cancers is proportional to BMI. Compared to those with a normal BMI, the risk of developing cancer is 8% higher for those with a BMI between 25-29.9 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. This increases with each class of BMI, up to 62% higher risk for those with a BMI above 40 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Not only does cancer risk increase, but so too does mortality. For each 5 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E increase in BMI, there is a 10% increase in cancer mortality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esedentary lifestyle\u003C/strong\u003E is indeed a risk factor for CRC, as physical inactivity has been associated with an increased risk. However, the magnitude of risk increase is generally lower than that associated with obesity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDaily \u003Cstrong\u003Easpirin\u003C/strong\u003E use over a duration of years is actually correlated with a decreased incidence and decreased mortality of colorectal cancer. Therefore, in this case, aspirin use would be considered protective rather than a risk factor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIschaemic heart disease\u003C/strong\u003E itself is not a direct risk factor for colorectal cancer. However, it shares some common risk factors with CRC, such as obesity and sedentary lifestyle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s \u003Cstrong\u003Eage\u003C/strong\u003E of 45 years is indeed a risk factor for colorectal cancer, as the incidence increases with age, particularly after 45. Colorectal cancer is now occurring with increasing frequency in the younger age groups. However in the context of this question, the BMI represents a more significant and potentially modifiable risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note that the relationship between these factors and CRC risk is complex and multifactorial. While BMI is identified as the highest risk factor among the given options, a comprehensive assessment would consider the interplay of multiple risk factors, including diet, family history, and other lifestyle factors not mentioned in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["High BMI is an important and modifiable risk factor for many diseases, including colon cancer.","The relationship between various lifestyle factors and colorectal cancer risk is complex and multifactorial."],"references":["Basen-Engquist K, Chang M. Obesity and cancer risk: recent review and evidence. Curr oncol rep. 2011;13(1):71-6. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3786180/","Johnson CM, Wei C, Ensor JE, Smolenski DJ, Amos CI, Levin B, et all. Meta-analyses of colorectal cancer risk factors. Cancer Causes Control. 2013;24(6):1207-22. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23563998/","O\u0027Sullivan DE, Sutherland RL, Town S, et al. Risk Factors for Early-Onset Colorectal Cancer: A Systematic Review and Meta-analysis. Clin Gastroenterol Hepatol. 2022; 20:1229-240."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85423"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11814"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85423"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-17T17:39:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-17T17:40:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4419"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102957"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"38","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/38"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diag